JavaScript Fetch Timeout and User Cancel: Stop Requests That Wait Forever

4 min read
3 hours ago

--

Press enter or click to view image in full size

fetch() is simple to start using:
const response = await fetch('/api/data');But there is an important default:
Fetch does not set a time limit for you.
If the server is slow, unreachable, or never sends a response, the promise can keep waiting.
That means a loading spinner can stay on screen much longer than it should.
The fix is to give requests a deadline. For requests a user can abandon, also give them a Cancel action.
1. Add a timeout to Fetch
Modern JavaScript provides AbortSignal.timeout(). It creates a signal that aborts itself after a number of milliseconds.
const response = await fetch('/api/data', {
signal: AbortSignal.timeout(5_000),
});const data = await response.json();This request gets five seconds. If it has not completed by then, Fetch rejects instead of waiting forever.
There is no setTimeout, no manual AbortController, and no timer to clean up. The platform manages the timeout.
Use a timeout that makes sense for the job. A search suggestion may deserve one or two seconds. A report that users expect to take longer may need more.
2. Handle a timeout in the UI
When AbortSignal.timeout() stops a Fetch request, the error usually has the name TimeoutError.
try {
const response = await fetch('/api/data', {
signal: AbortSignal.timeout(5_000),
}); if (!response.ok) {
throw new Error(`Request failed: ${response.status}`);
} const data = await response.json();
renderData(data);
} catch (error) {
if (error.name === 'TimeoutError') {
showMessage('This is taking too long. Please try again.');
} else {
showMessage('Something went wrong. Please try again.');
}
}Keep a timeout separate from an ordinary server error. A timeout often calls for a Retry button. A validation error or a 404 calls for a different response.
3. Let the user cancel a request
A timeout is automatic. User cancellation needs an AbortController, because your code needs something it can call when the user presses Cancel.
const controller = new AbortController();cancelButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
controller.abort();
});const response = await fetch('/api/data', {
signal: controller.signal,
});Calling controller.abort() tells Fetch to stop the in-progress request. The Fetch promise rejects, so you should handle that outcome too.
On its own, this gives the user control, but it does not add a deadline. A request still waits forever if the user never clicks Cancel.
4. Use both a timeout and user cancellation
Real requests often need both controls:

• The user may press Cancel.

• The server may take too long.
AbortSignal.any() merges multiple signals into one. The first signal to abort stops the request.
const controller = new AbortController();cancelButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
controller.abort();
});const signal = AbortSignal.any([
controller.signal,
AbortSignal.timeout(5_000),
]);const response = await fetch('/api/data', { signal });You only pass one signal to Fetch. Behind the scenes, it listens to both the user action and the five-second clock.
Whichever happens first wins. If the user cancels at two seconds, the request stops at two seconds. If they do nothing and five seconds pass, the timeout stops it.
5. Give each outcome the right experience
User cancellation is usually not an error worth showing. They asked to stop. A timeout is different because it tells you that the request did not finish in time.
async function loadData() {
const controller = new AbortController();
const signal = AbortSignal.any([
controller.signal,
AbortSignal.timeout(5_000),
]); cancelButton.onclick = () => controller.abort(); try {
setLoading(true); const response = await fetch('/api/data', { signal }); if (!response.ok) {
throw new Error(`Request failed: ${response.status}`);
} const data = await response.json();
renderData(data);
} catch (error) {
if (error.name === 'TimeoutError') {
showRetryMessage('The request timed out. Try again.');
} else if (error.name !== 'AbortError') {
showMessage('Unable to load data. Please try again.');
}
} finally {
setLoading(false);
}
}The finally block matters for the UI. It runs whether the request succeeds, times out, is cancelled, or fails for another reason. That makes it a good place to stop the spinner and re-enable controls.
6. Why Fetch timeouts matter on the server too
Timeouts are not only a browser concern.
Imagine your server calls a third-party API. If that API hangs, your server can keep a socket and other resources busy while it waits. Enough hanging calls can fill the available connection pool and slow down unrelated requests.
Use a deadline for network calls you do not fully control. It limits how long one slow dependency can affect the rest of your service.
7. The Axios version
Axios accepts the same standard AbortSignal. You can use the exact same AbortController, AbortSignal.timeout(), and AbortSignal.any() pattern.
import axios from 'axios';async function loadDataWithAxios() {
const controller = new AbortController();
const signal = AbortSignal.any([
controller.signal,
AbortSignal.timeout(5_000),
]); cancelButton.onclick = () => controller.abort(); try {
setLoading(true); const response = await axios.get('/api/data', { signal });
renderData(response.data);
} catch (error) {
if (error.code === 'ERR_CANCELED') {
if (signal.reason?.name === 'TimeoutError') {
showRetryMessage('The request timed out. Try again.');
}
// Otherwise the user cancelled. Do not show an error message.
} else {
showMessage('Unable to load data. Please try again.');
}
} finally {
setLoading(false);
}
}Axios reports both kinds of abort with error.code === 'ERR_CANCELED'. Check signal.reason when you need to tell a timeout apart from a user cancellation.
The rule to remember
Every network request can be slow, fail, or never respond. Give it a sensible timeout. If the user can leave the task, give them a Cancel button too.
With Fetch, that usually means AbortSignal.timeout() for a deadline and AbortSignal.any() when you also need user cancellation.

